THERE WAS A BOY WHO LIVED IN THE LIBRARY WITH HIS MOM AND DAD.
THIS WAS IN THE 1940'S IN NEW YORK CITY.
RAYMOND CLARK TOLD HIS PARENTS THAT HE WAS GLAD THAT THEY WERE RICH.
HIS FATHER ALMOST CHOKED, WHILE HIS MOM CORRECTED HIM AND SAYS THAT THEY ARE ACTUALLY POOR.
AFTER HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AT THE LIBRARY AS A CUSTODIAN, THEY ALL MOVED IN TO LIVE THERE.
AT FIRST, RAYMOND WAS ASHAMED BECAUSE HE WOULD GET TEASED ABOUT LIVING IN THE LIBRARY.
AFTER A WHILE, THOUGH, RAYMOND BECAME VERY GRATEFUL FOR THAT EXPERIENCE.
HE WOULD READ UNTIL 3 O'CLOCK IN THE MORNING.
HE WOULD RUN AROUND AFTER HOURS AND SCREAM AND PLAY.
RAYMOND SAYS THAT GROWING UP IN THE LIBRARY GAVE HIM THE THIRST FOR LEARNING.
HE LATER BECAME THE FIRST PERSON IN HIS FAMILY TO ATTEND COLLEGE.
AFTER GRADUATING, HE LANDED A TEACHING POSITION.
WHEN HE SHOWED HIS FATHER HIS PLAQUE ON HIS DOOR WITH HIS NAME ON IT, THE FATHER WAS CLEARLY ELATED.
RAYMOND FINISHES BY SAYING THAT HE CAN'T IMAGINE NOT EVER HAVING LIVED IN THE LIBRARY.
RONALD CLARK WAS A KID IN THE 1940S
ONE DAY HE TOLD HIS PARENTS THAT HE WAS HAPPY THAT THEY WERE RICH.
HIS FATHER ALMOST CHOKED ON HIS FOOD WHILE HIS MOTHER CORRECTED HIM SAYING THAT THEY WERE ACTUALLY POOR.
HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AT THE LIBRARY AS A CUSTODIAN.
THE FAMILY MOVED IN TO THE LIBRARY AND LIVED THERE FOR MANY YEARS.
HIS FATHER WOULD WAX THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES AND CLEAN UNTIL EVERYTHING SHINED.
AT FIRST, RONALD WAS ASHAMED BECAUSE HIS PEERS WOULD TEASE HIM ABOUT LIVING IN THE LIBRARY.
BUT, AFTER A WHILE RONALD BECAME VERY GRATEFUL.
HE WOULD STAY UP READING UNTIL 3 O'CLOCK IN THE MORNING.
RONALD SAYS THAT THE LIBRARY IS WHAT GAVE HIM THE THIRST FOR LEARNING.
HE WAS THE FIRST OF HIS FAMILY TO ATTEND COLLEGE.
AFTER COLLEGE, RONALD GOT A TEACHING POSITION.
HE SHOWED HIS FATHER THE PLAQUE WITH HIS NAME ON IT.
HIS FATHER WAS QUIET, BUT RONALD COULD TELL THAT HE WAS VERY PROUD OF HIM.
HE FINISHES BY SAYING THAT HE COULD NOT IMAGINE HOW HIS LIFE WOULD HAVE BEEN LIKE IF HE HADN'T GROWN UP IN THE LIBRARY.
